0.body: Simple file system implementation using the 9P protocol froggr is a modern implementation of the Plan 9 filesystem protocol (9P), focusing on providing flexible namespace management through bind operations.

1.body: The 9P protocol is a network protocol developed for the Plan 9 operating system, designed to provide transparent access to resources across a network. One of its key features is the ability to manipulate the namespace through operations like bind.
1.title: What is 9P?

10.body: Froggr implements a 9P filesystem server that: Handles client requests Manages namespace operations Provides filesystem access Maintains session state
10.title: 5. Server-Based Architecture

11.body: Each session's state is: Persisted in /tmp/proc/ Tracked independently Cleaned up automatically Recoverable after crashes
11.title: 6. State Management

12.body: The system is designed with clear separation between: Filesystem operations Namespace management Session handling State persistence Client interactions

12.title: 7. Clean Separation of Concerns

13.body: Froggr favors explicit operations: Clear bind modes Visible namespace changes Traceable state modifications Documented side effects

14.body: Operations are designed to: Validate inputs Check permissions Handle errors gracefully Clean up on failure Maintain consistency
14.title: 9. Fail-Safe Operations

15.body: While inspired by Plan 9, Froggr integrates well with Unix systems: Works with existing filesystems Respects Unix permissions Uses familiar path conventions Provides Unix-like tools
15.title: 10. Unix Integration

16.body: The bind operation is one of the fundamental mechanisms in Froggr's namespace management system. It allows for dynamic modification of the filesystem view by overlaying directories and files.
16.breadcrumbs: Design Principles ¬ª Bind Operations Design ¬ª Bind Operation Design
16.title: Bind Operation Design

17.body: Bind Operation Process The bind operation follows a specific process flow: Request Initiation Client sends bind request with source and target paths Bind mode is specified (Replace, Before, After, Create) Validation Source path existence check Target path validation Permission verification Mode-specific requirements check Namespace Update Current namespace state is preserved New binding is created according to specified mode Namespace tree is updated Changes are atomically applied State Management Session state is updated New binding is recorded State is persisted to disk Recovery information is saved Completion Success/failure status is determined Client is notified of result Namespace becomes immediately consistent
17.breadcrumbs: Design Principles ¬ª Bind Operations Design ¬ª Process Overview
17.title: Process Overview

18.title: Key Design Aspects

19.body: All bind operations are atomic Namespace remains consistent during updates Failures result in complete rollback

22.body: Multiple bind modes supported Dynamic namespace modification Runtime configuration possible Stackable directory views This design ensures that bind operations are reliable, predictable, and maintainable while providing the flexibility needed for complex namespace configurations.

22.title: Flexibility

23.body: The P9 protocol for file systems requires a unique feature called bind, which allows for flexible control over the namespace (file hierarchy). The bind operation maps a file, directory, or another namespace tree into a new location in the namespace.
23.title: Bind Operations

24.body: froggr supports four binding modes: Replace Mode : Replace existing content Before Mode : Add content with higher priority After Mode : Add content with lower priority Create Mode : Create mountpoint if needed Each mode provides different behaviors for resolving file lookups when multiple resources are mapped to the same namespace.
24.title: Available Modes

25.body: The Replace mode is the default binding mode in froggr. It completely replaces whatever was previously mounted at the mountpoint with the new source.
25.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations ¬ª Replace Mode ¬ª Replace Mode
25.title: Replace Mode

27.body: The src completely overrides any existing content at the mountpoint. After the bind operation, only the contents of src will be visible at the specified mountpoint.
27.title: Behavior

29.body: Temporarily replace a default configuration directory with a test version: frg bind /test/config /etc After this command, processes will see /test/config contents instead of the original /etc.
29.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations ¬ª Replace Mode ¬ª Replacing Configuration Directory
29.title: Replacing Configuration Directory

3.body: Getting Started Bind Operations CLI Reference
3.title: Quick Links

30.body: Redirect access to /bin to a custom toolchain directory for development: frg bind /custom/tools/bin /bin This replaces the system binaries with your custom tools.
30.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations ¬ª Replace Mode ¬ª Custom Toolchain
30.title: Custom Toolchain

31.body: The Before mode places the new source before the existing contents of the mountpoint in the lookup order.
31.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations ¬ª Before Mode ¬ª Before Mode
31.title: Before Mode

33.body: When a lookup occurs, froggr searches src first, and if the file isn't found there, it searches the original mountpoint. This creates a layered view where new content takes precedence over existing content.
33.title: Behavior

35.body: Add custom binaries that take precedence over system binaries: frg bind -b /custom/bin /bin In this case, /custom/bin/ls will be used instead of /bin/ls if both exist, while other commands will fall back to /bin.
35.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations ¬ª Before Mode ¬ª Custom Binary Directory
35.title: Custom Binary Directory

36.body: Prioritize development versions of libraries: frg bind -b /dev/libs /usr/lib This allows testing new library versions while maintaining access to the system libraries as fallback.
36.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations ¬ª Before Mode ¬ª Development Libraries
36.title: Development Libraries

37.body: The After mode appends the new source to the mountpoint's search path, making it a fallback option.
37.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations ¬ª After Mode ¬ª After Mode
37.title: After Mode

39.body: froggr resolves lookups by searching the original mountpoint first, and if the file isn't found there, it checks the src. This maintains existing content's priority while providing additional fallback options.
39.title: Behavior

41.body: Add extra fonts while maintaining system defaults: frg bind -a /extra/fonts /fonts System fonts remain the primary source, with additional fonts available when needed.
41.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations ¬ª After Mode ¬ª Additional Fonts
41.title: Additional Fonts

42.body: Add supplementary configuration files: frg bind -a /additional/config /etc This ensures /etc retains its default behavior but gains additional configuration files when defaults don't exist.
42.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations ¬ª After Mode ¬ª Configuration Extensions
42.title: Configuration Extensions

43.body: The Create mode ensures the mountpoint exists before performing the bind operation.
43.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations ¬ª Create Mode ¬ª Create Mode
43.title: Create Mode

45.body: Before performing the bind operation, froggr checks if the mountpoint exists. If it doesn't, the directory is created automatically. After creation (if needed), it performs a standard replace binding.
45.title: Behavior

47.body: Create and bind a custom log directory: frg bind -c /data/logs /var/log/app This creates /var/log/app if it doesn't exist, then binds /data/logs to it.
47.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations ¬ª Create Mode ¬ª Log Directory Setup
47.title: Log Directory Setup

48.body: Set up a new development environment: frg bind -c /dev/workspace/bin /opt/tools Creates /opt/tools if needed, then binds the workspace binaries.
48.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations ¬ª Create Mode ¬ª Development Environment
48.title: Development Environment

49.body: Union directories allow you to combine multiple sources into a single view, creating a merged namespace.
49.title: Union Directories

5.body: Froggr is built on several key design principles that guide its development and usage:
5.title: Design Principles

50.body: You can create union directories by using multiple bind operations with different modes. The order of operations matters, as it determines the lookup priority.
50.title: Creating Union Directories

51.body:
frg bind -b /local/bin /bin
frg bind -a /backup/bin /bin This creates a three-layer union: /local/bin (highest priority) Original /bin (middle priority) /backup/bin (lowest priority)
51.title: Basic Example

53.body:
Create a layered development environment: frg bind -b /dev/override /usr
frg bind -a /dev/fallback /usr This allows: Development files to override system files System files to serve as the default Fallback files for missing components
53.title: Development Environment

54.body:
Manage multiple configuration sources: frg bind -b /etc/custom /etc
frg bind -a /etc/defaults /etc This creates a hierarchy where: Custom configurations take precedence System configurations remain as default Default configurations serve as fallback
54.title: Configuration Management

6.body: Froggr draws heavy inspiration from Plan 9's filesystem architecture, particularly its approach to namespace management. Like Plan 9, Froggr treats everything as a file and uses filesystem operations to manage system resources.
6.title: 1. Plan 9 Inspiration

60.body:
Bind a source directory to a mountpoint. frg bind [OPTIONS] <SOURCE> <MOUNTPOINT> Options -b, --before: Bind source before existing content -a, --after: Bind source after existing content -c, --create: Create mountpoint if it doesn't exist -r, --recursive: Recursively bind subdirectories Examples # Replace binding
frg bind /source /dest # Before binding with mountpoint creation
frg bind -b -c /custom/bin /opt/tools # After binding
frg bind -a /fallback/config /etc
60.title: bind

7.body: Each Froggr session maintains its own filesystem namespace, similar to Plan 9's per-process namespaces. This isolation allows for: Independent namespace modifications Process-specific views of the filesystem Clean separation between different applications or services
